# Bitrecs Roadmap for 2025

Here's a rough timeline of updates we are working on:
## Early September

- 0.8.7 introduces reasoning/sku scoring into the validator reward logic

The goal here is to add more separation between miners and foster some competition by doing a more thorough scoring eval. Right now the network is stagnant with low quality (but fast!) recs which are not ideal for customer demos. Imagine shopping for a grand piano and being recommended a dj mixer? Or shopping for pet food and being recommended sunglasses.

Partially inspired by const tweet regarding a dual system: https://x.com/const_reborn/status/1956712435202560344

We have created a web2 network called Perseus - which only calls vetted closed models and have been utilizing this for demos and beta testing stores. So far the feedback has been positive but the actual 'mix' of models matters and we're still iterating to find the ideal composition. We're also building a training set for a future fine-tune that should help with more robust scoring via the validators. From an application point of view the extension app will have the ability to A/B test between Bitrecs and Perseus natively. We're exploring if this setup can be a sub-subnet or a group of miners inside this subnet, but would require some major reworking of the topology and incentives - stay tuned.

Longer reasoning yields better recs but latency matters a lot in ecommerce. The latest trend of hybrid/tunable reasoning models is notable. If this trend continues then we may explore giving merchants an optional 'dial' they can adjust directly - which modifies synapse timeouts per request, reflecting how long they want the network to 'think' for them. A more sensible middle ground could be a greedy pre-fetch of several product requests to the network - so miners can grind out longer thinking times behind the scenes, increasing the quality of the recs. We're loosening synapse times to 8 seconds for this release.

## Q4 2025

- 0.8.8 verified inference proxy

A simple opt-in proxy for miners to provide verifiability of inference. 
More details on this soon along with concrete examples of what are considered 'good' vs 'garbage' recommendations.

- 0.8.9 move all sku scoring/reasoning to the validators and remove offchain/blackbox scoring entirely for transparency
- GA release of the extension app

## 2026

- We're exploring a unique token model which would tie ecommerce store performance directly to the alpha supply (inversely). Simply put, more sales and engagement generated by the subnet via recommendations would decrease the float of alpha on an ongoing basis. This could better align all stakeholders and accrue value to alpha more consistently but we're still modeling this out and will have more information on what direction we're going later this year. 

As a friendly reminder this channel is for dev support of the underlying subnet code and github only, please refrain from talking about alpha price/tokens here, thank you.

state of the network

# Update 0.8.7 - Reasoning Update/Burn

**Released:** Sept 27, 2025  

Updated scoring to incorporate Reasoning and SKU Relevance

**BREAKING CHANGES:** Miners/Validators must update nodes

### Scoring
- Added miner reasoning reports for scoring measurement
- Miners are adjusted by reasoning f_score in reward
- f_score has two eval components (Rules/LLM) computed offchain
- Removed scoring ceiling

### Emission Burn
- Implementing an emission burn starting at 95%
- Burn will reduce over time as rec quality improves and competition increases

### Consensus
- Wider top_n set for consensus selection
- Removed orphan handling/QoS pathing
- Improved consistency of batch scoring
- Consensus requirements adjusted to encourage more model diversity
- Consensus winner gets 5% bonus

### Prompting
- Added common ecommerce/promotion events
- Updated season to Fall/Winter
- Added more fine grained seasonality control 

### General
- Increased dendrite timeout to 7 seconds
- Added reasoning parameters for OPEN_ROUTER/CHAT_GPT
- Updated logging to be more consistent across batches

All,

We're happy to release our 0.8.7 update which includes reasoning and scoring updates.
However given the unsatisfactory state of the network due to misaligned incentives, we're enabling a 95% emission burn until we fix the underlying issues.
The burn rate will decay proportional to network performance/rec quality over time and as new features rollout (i.e verified inference in the next release).

https://github.com/bitrecs/bitrecs-subnet/pull/15

We're going to merge this PR **tomorrow 12pm UTC**, please have your nodes ready to update by then.

Thanks for your continued support.

Hey all,

For those enjoying the spicy chat logs I'll offer some insight, apologies for the wall of text:

Bitrecs was created with the idea that the latest LLMs so called 'state of the art' are trained on more and more relevant data increasing their internal knowledge of shopping, products, catalogs, attributes, customer behavior, returns, marketing metrics etc - all the core signals that are vital to ecommerce success. LLM's also have an incredible (some would say magical) ability to personify anyone or anything - so why not have an LLM act like an ecommerce merchant or personal shopper? We asked what if we could tap/use this knowledge directly in a real-time recommendation scenario for online shoppers?  

We're seeing longer context, zero shot approaches to querying LLM's work across many different disciplines so lets apply this directly to ecommerce. We built this subnet to test this idea - lets gather all the relevant information at the critical time of decision making during shopping - ask **many** LLM's what they think and consolidate their results using a novel consensus algorithm.  Perhaps this will yield superior recommendations that convert, or at the very least provide a set of products that would offer something different to the customer - a different but relevant perspective on the inventory. But make no mistake none of this is for certain - its one giant science experiment using live customers as the subjects against realtime LLMs calls. The true measure of conversion is real-world clicks, add to carts and sales - but to get to this point a lot has to come together and incentives need to be aligned.

We built and launched the subnet with live sites - and quickly found out that unless the incentive mechanism is rock solid, it will quickly get exploited by the community and race to the lowest common denominator - for this subnet in particular, exploitation isn't the end of the world - its just a very poor user experience - bad, random recs with non-sensical reasoning being displayed to customers that simply do not convert. This caused some of our merchants to question the underlying tech so we made the decision to pull live traffic from the subnet and divert it all to an 'honest' web2 network until we could fix the incentives.

The honest web2 network (Perseus) references and uses the exact same prompting and consensus code from Bitrecs - it just 100% calls real vetted models and we rotate in the latest models weekly (i.e grok4 fast and gemini-2.5-flash-lite-preview-09-2025 are the current top models for us). The results are very positive: way better recommendations that actually show signs of 'intelligent' personified-selection and higher conversions. The merchants love this solution. We also love it because it can scale across multiple dimensions - we can add more nodes to make it more robust, we can add different models to increase diversity of opinion and we can also plug in 0-day models as soon as they are released with no downtime and instantly get an upgrade on intelligence/performance. Additionally, the entire recommendation engine can be controlled by a simple text prompt dramatically altering the behavior of the system and resulting recommendations. It also fully generalizes which is a sleeper feature that enables us to rapidly light up merchants without having to fine tune or customize to specific ecommerce verticals. **From having zero AI to a SOTA battery of LLMs installed in 5 minutes for merchants too busy to keep up with the rapidly shifting landscape of AI - this is the true unlock.**

So this leads us to today and the current 95% miner emission burn - if we're not sending real traffic into the subnet and the subnet is fully gamed and dominated by a few miners who play hardball (i.e ddosing honest miners) then we're going to do whatever is in our power to dis-incentivize this behavior until we can regroup and fix the incentives. No value creation = no/low emissions. This is accepted and fully acknowledged by our team, we know what we signed up for...do you?

This is what we're doing now: fixing the incentives and miner substrate to make mining fair again and hope to bring back live sites into the network after we're confident the mechanism is functioning correctly.
When incentives are fixed and the subnet is producing acceptable recs we'll lift the burn and start pushing live traffic into the network. 

If you are looking for someone to blame for the current state of the subnet please direct it all towards me. I take full responsibility and if we're not delivering than you are more than welcome to vote both your feet and by your wallet. You can sling insults my way and question my ability, use GPT to write scathing rebuttals, question my character, ethics, race, hairstyle, whatever... I've been around the block so believe me this isn't my first rodeo and can handle the criticism 🙂

This is the beauty of an open and permissionless network like Bittensor - nobody is forcing you to do anything and you are free to engage or disengage at anytime. For us at Bitrecs, we're fully committed to building and seeing this idea through even it means breaking a few eggs before the omelet gets made. We hope you will stay along for the journey - but hold nothing against you if you decide to move on, salute.
